  "summary": "Following his heart attack, Hercule Poirot informs Hastings that he will not seek further medical attention. Despite his failing physical health, which includes paralysis and heart issues, Poirot maintains that his mind remains sharp. He declares that this will be his last case, driven by the need to identify the cunning murderer he calls \"X,\" whose methods he has yet to decipher. Hastings, however, privately doubts Poirot's mental acuity in light of the recent death of Mrs. Franklin and the near-death of Mrs. Littler.\n\nThe following day, Poirot agrees to see Dr. John Franklin, a researcher. After examining Poirot, Franklin informs a worried Hastings that Poirot's physical condition is \"terrible\" and that his time is running out. Franklin notes that Poirot is aware of his terminal state and is motivated by a sense of responsibility to complete his work. The only available treatment for Poirot is the use of nitroglycerin vials to manage potential attacks.\n\nFranklin shares a detached philosophy regarding death, stating that medicine should improve human life rather than merely delay the inevitable. He reveals that he is set to depart for a position in Africa in ten days. During their conversation, Franklin also discusses his personal life, admitting to being a selfish and stubborn man. He confesses to a lack of grief regarding the death of his wife, Barbara, noting that he moved on from their marriage quickly.",
